<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8"/>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"/>
<title>Sector Momentum — Sentiment</title>
<script src="{{ plotly_bundle }}"></script>
<style>
{% include "_style.html.j2" %}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Header -->
<header>
  <h1 data-i18n="title">Sector momentum</h1>
  <span class="scan-date"><span data-i18n="lastScan">Last scan:</span> {% if active_scan_id %}#{{ active_scan_id }} · {% endif %}{{ scan_date }}</span>
  <div class="segment-toggle" role="tablist" aria-label="Dashboard segment">
    <a class="segment-btn" href="index.html" data-i18n="segment_sectors">Sectors</a>
    <a class="segment-btn" href="themes.html" data-i18n="segment_themes">Themes</a>
    <span class="segment-btn active" aria-current="page" data-i18n="segment_sentiment">Sentiment</span>
  </div>
  <span class="disclaimer" data-i18n="disclaimer">Analytical tooling, not investment advice.</span>
  <button id="guide-open-btn" class="guide-open-btn" type="button" aria-label="Open guide" data-i18n="guide_open_btn">Guide</button>
  <button id="lang-toggle" class="lang-toggle" type="button" onclick="toggleLang()" aria-label="Switch language">SV</button>
</header>

<section class="tab-panel active">
  <p class="tab-note" data-i18n="note_sentiment">Sentiment weighting affects the leaderboard ranking only.</p>
  <details class="tab-guide">
    <summary data-i18n="guide_summary_sentiment">How is the sentiment score calculated?</summary>
    <div class="tab-guide-body" data-i18n-html="guide_body_sentiment">
      <h4>Source — Google Trends only</h4>
      <p>Sentiment measures <strong>search attention</strong> using Google Trends.
         Reddit and news-headline sources were evaluated and dropped — no reliable
         free access.</p>
      <h4>Method</h4>
      <p>For each sector we pull ~13 weeks of worldwide search interest for its primary
         keyword (e.g. Technology&nbsp;→&nbsp;<em>semiconductor</em>,
         Energy&nbsp;→&nbsp;<em>oil</em>). The headline score is the
         <strong>trend (slope)</strong> of that interest, standardized across the
         11 sectors (z-score):
         <span class="signal-hi">positive = rising attention vs peers</span>,
         <span class="signal-lo">negative = fading</span>.
         Where a ticker maps to a known Google Knowledge&nbsp;Graph <strong>entity</strong>,
         we query that entity rather than the raw ticker string, to avoid name
         collisions (e.g. a ticker that is also a common word); tickers without a
         known entity fall back to the plain string.
         Interest is pulled per region — <strong>US</strong> sectors in US search,
         <strong>EU</strong> sectors averaged across Germany, France and the UK —
         and normalized against a neutral, ubiquitous anchor term rather than a
         market ticker. (This anchor change means sentiment values from before it
         are not directly comparable to later ones.)</p>
      <h4>Derived signals</h4>
      <p>From the same interest series we read out a few complementary views (shown
         in the table below, information-only — only Momentum can affect the ranking):</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Momentum</strong> — the trend/slope, same series the headline
            score is built from.</li>
        <li><strong>Acceleration</strong> — recent-half slope minus earlier-half
            slope; positive means attention is picking up speed.</li>
        <li><strong>Range position</strong> — where the latest reading sits within
            its own 13-week min–max (0% = window low, 100% = window high).</li>
        <li><strong>Spike</strong> — z-score of the latest point vs the trailing
            weeks; a breakout in interest.</li>
        <li><strong>Volatility</strong> — how choppy week-to-week interest has been.</li>
        <li><strong>Attention</strong> — relative search interest compared
            head-to-head against all other sectors in the same region.
            Higher = more attention.</li>
      </ul>
      <h4>It does not drive the ranking by default</h4>
      <p>The leaderboard composite is built from price/momentum signals only. Sentiment
         changes the ranking <em>only</em> when you enable the <strong>Sentiment
         toggle</strong>, at the weight you choose. Treat it as a confirmer, not a
         driver — search interest is noisy and can lag price.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <div class="chart-container" id="sentiment-scatter" style="height:560px"></div>
  <p style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:0.8rem;padding:8px 0 0 4px">
    Bottom-right quadrant (data ahead of sentiment) is the early-rotation zone.
    Hollow points = no sentiment data this scan (source unavailable or EU-only).
    Sentiment is a confirming signal — noisy, gameable, retail-biased.
    This is analytical tooling, not investment advice.
  </p>

  {% if sentiment_signal_rows %}
  <h3 style="margin:24px 0 8px 4px" data-i18n="sent_derived_heading">Derived Trends signals</h3>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_sector">Sector</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_region">Region</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_momentum">Momentum</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_acceleration">Acceleration</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_range">Range&nbsp;pos.</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_spike">Spike</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_volatility">Volatility</th>
          <th data-i18n="sent_col_attention">Attention</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {% for r in sentiment_signal_rows %}
        <tr>
          <td>{{ r.sector }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.region }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.momentum }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.acceleration }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.range_position }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.spike }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.volatility }}</td>
          <td>{{ r.attention }}</td>
        </tr>
        {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  {% endif %}
</section>

<script>
var SENTIMENT_DATA = {{ sentiment_scatter_json | safe }};
Plotly.newPlot('sentiment-scatter', SENTIMENT_DATA.data, SENTIMENT_DATA.layout, {responsive: true});

{% include "_i18n.html.j2" %}
</script>

{% include "_guide_modal.html.j2" %}

</body>
</html>
